00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:32.770
Irish Traffic Police Accidentally Invented
their own Supervillain

00:01:32.770 --> 00:01:37.731
Not so long ago, the name Prawo Jazdy struck
fear into the hearts of Ireland’s traffic

00:01:37.731 --> 00:01:38.731
cops.

00:01:38.731 --> 00:01:42.740
A Polish immigrant, Mr. Jazdy was also the
most prolific petty-criminal the Garda had

00:01:42.740 --> 00:01:43.740
ever encountered.

00:01:43.740 --> 00:01:47.840
Over the course of two short years, he racked
up over 50 speeding tickets in every part

00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:48.840
of the island.

00:01:48.840 --> 00:01:50.700
Stranger still, he’d never been caught.

00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:51.799
It gets weirder.

00:01:51.799 --> 00:01:54.509
Mr. Jazdy was a master of disguise.

00:01:54.509 --> 00:01:57.320
Sometimes he’d be dressed as a middle-aged
man when he was stopped.

00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:59.250
Other times he’d be dressed as a young woman.

00:01:59.250 --> 00:02:02.909
Irish traffic cops found he’d given them
a different driver’s license every time

00:02:02.909 --> 00:02:03.909
they’d stopped him.

00:02:03.909 --> 00:02:07.200
He’d given 50 different home addresses,
and 50 different dates of birth.

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:12.010
Eventually, a special task force was assigned
to catch this international man of mystery.

00:02:12.010 --> 00:02:16.040
At which point a native Polish speaker joined
the Garda’s traffic division.

00:02:16.040 --> 00:02:20.000
He took one look at Mr. Jazdy’s file and
probably fell down laughing.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:22.780
Y’see, Prawo Jazdy wasn’t a supervillain.

00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:24.880
He wasn’t even a person at all.

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:28.300
Prawo Jazdy is Polish for ‘driver’s license’.

00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:31.850
According to the BBC, Ireland’s confused
traffic cops had spent 2 years writing up

00:02:31.850 --> 00:02:35.460
tickets for different Polish drivers under
the assumption that they were all the same

00:02:35.460 --> 00:02:36.460
person.

00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:40.510
The mistake was finally discovered in 2009,
to the embarrassment of all.

