00:02:41.510 --> 00:02:44.410
The State of Maine Has More Black Bears than
Black People

00:02:44.410 --> 00:02:48.770
The northeasternmost state of the US, Maine
is one of the most-rural places in America.

00:02:48.770 --> 00:02:53.700
With a population of 1.33 million, it’s
not the emptiest state, but it’s definitely

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:55.020
kinda lonesome.

00:02:55.020 --> 00:02:58.570
It’s also one of the whitest places in the
whole of the States.

00:02:58.570 --> 00:03:00.120
How do we know this?

00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:03.860
Because according to data from both the state
of Maine and the US Census, Maine has more

00:03:03.860 --> 00:03:06.160
black bears than it has black people.

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:08.820
Seriously, it ain’t even close.

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:13.530
The last US Census recorded roughly 19,000
African-Americans living in Maine.

00:03:13.530 --> 00:03:17.450
A couple of years before, the state of Maine
estimated its black bear population at roughly

00:03:17.450 --> 00:03:18.450
36,000.

00:03:18.450 --> 00:03:23.630
In other words, there are roughly two black
bears for every single black person in Maine.

00:03:23.630 --> 00:03:27.480
That’s a crazy figure, especially if you
grew up in a big city, or in the South, or

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:30.670
on the West Coast, or, well, anywhere but
Maine.

00:03:30.670 --> 00:03:34.750
Nationally, black people make up 13.2% of
the US population.

00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:36.660
In Maine, they make up just 1.4%.

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:41.170
By contrast, if black bears were people, they’d
make up 2.7%.

