00:03:42.490 --> 00:03:45.150
Congress Name-Checks Hitler Seven Times a
Month

00:03:45.150 --> 00:03:46.150
hitler

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:49.300
Godwin’s Law states that the longer an argument
goes on, the greater the chance of someone

00:03:49.300 --> 00:03:50.300
bringing up Hitler.

00:03:50.300 --> 00:03:53.860
It further states that, the minute Hitler
comparisons are invoked, the conversation

00:03:53.860 --> 00:03:54.860
becomes worthless.

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:58.500
Which, when you think about it, is the perfect
way of describing Congress.

00:03:58.500 --> 00:04:02.820
Both parties have been engaged in a never-ending
argument for decades now, and both have essentially

00:04:02.820 --> 00:04:04.130
become worthless.

00:04:04.130 --> 00:04:07.650
We know this because they just can’t stop
bringing up Hitler.

00:04:07.650 --> 00:04:12.060
The nonprofit Sunlight Foundation tracks all
words in the official Congressional record

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:14.120
for their Capitol Words project.

00:04:14.120 --> 00:04:18.370
The database stretches back to 1996, and contains
millions of words.

00:04:18.370 --> 00:04:23.590
In 2015, they crunched the numbers for Hitler,
and found Congress name-checked the Nazi dictator

00:04:23.590 --> 00:04:26.470
an average of seven times a month.

00:04:26.470 --> 00:04:30.370
Hitler has been compared in Congress to Saddam
Hussein, to global warming, to modern China,

00:04:30.370 --> 00:04:34.880
to Gaddafi’s Libya, to Sudan, to Iran, to
ISIS, to the cloning of human beings, to the

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:38.700
American military, and (bizarrely) to the
Founding Fathers.

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:40.760
No other dictator even comes close.

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:46.700
The high point came in 2003, when Hitler was
mentioned 93 times in a single month.

00:04:46.700 --> 00:04:52.040
Republicans mention Hitler slightly-more often,
with 57% of mentions to the Dem’s 43%.

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:58.080
But, as the Daily Dot pointed out, no party
has yet been known to mention Godwin’s Law.

